1. Gets the thread manager instance using `ThreadManager::getInstance()`
2. Resets the thread manager state using `resetState()`
3. Creates a `ConditionalMutex` instance
4. Creates a `ConditionalLockGuard` in a scope block (thread safety disabled by default)
5. Attempts to lock the mutex using `try_lock()` without safety enabled
6. Automatically exits the guard scope when the block ends
7. Enables thread safety using `enableThreadSafety()`
8. Creates another `ConditionalLockGuard` in a scope block with safety enabled
9. Attempts to lock the mutex using `try_lock()` with safety enabled
10. Automatically exits the guard scope
